<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-460-947  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 460 947.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Sept 24 1990 n288 p64(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Countdown to 2000: at the turn of the century, MIS's problemscould increase a hundredfold. (Final Word) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sienko, Norm.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The dawning of a new millenium will cause several problems forcomputer users and MIS, and little help seems to be on the wayfrom hardware vendors or software publishers.andP;  Data files often donot accommodate four-digit 'year' fields, and in these casescomputers instructed to subtract, add or compare will run intoproblems when confronted with '90' and '00', which actuallyrepresents an increase of 10 years.andP;  Software developed to findtwo-digit year dates may not be intelligent enough to modify therequired file descriptions, procedural statements, job-controllanguage specifications and the like.andP;  MIS must analyze thecomplete program portfolio and files, make the necessary changesto accommodate the new century and test everything.andP;  This is goingto require considerable time and resources, but to date few MISexecutives seem interested in the process.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MISPlanningRecords ManagementFile ManagementTwentieth centuryTime Measurement.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>